wfIsdnBriTimer3Tmo.name: wfIsdnBriTimer3Tmo
wfIsdnBriTimer3Tmo.description: Indicates the amount of time in seconds for our T3 timer. The T3 timer is initiated by the host (i.e. the router). The T3 timer is started whenever the S/T interface is in a deactivated state and the host (i.e. the Router) wishes to activate the interface. As an example, for our application, the Router would activate the interface when there was data to be transmitted out that interface. At the point when we try activating the interface, the T3 timer is started. During the duration of the T3 timer, the router in trying to activate the interface will transmit INFO 1's out the S/T interface until either a signal is detected (from the network) or the T3 timer expires.

wfIsdnBriTimer4Tmo.name: wfIsdnBriTimer4Tmo
wfIsdnBriTimer4Tmo.description: Indicates the amount of time in milliseconds for our T4 timer. The T4 timer is a debounce timer which is used to shield the upper layers from short glitches at the S/T interface. Spurious problems of short duration will not be reported to the upper layers until the T4 timer expires. The T4 timer is started when leaving state F7 or F8 upon the reception of INFO 0. The corresponding Deactivation Indication will be delivered to layer 2 only if layer 1 does not enter an active state before expiration of this timer. (Note that a value of 0 indicates the timer is disabled).

wfIsdnBriTimer4Timeouts.name: wfIsdnBriTimer4Timeouts

wfIsdnBriLineType.name: wfIsdnBriLineType
wfIsdnBriLineType.description: BRI line type can be either Multipoint (passive bus configuration with more than one device connected) or Point-to-Point with a single device attached.

wfIsdnBriMode.name: wfIsdnBriMode
wfIsdnBriMode.description: This attribute controls the operation of the Basic Rate Interface. DIALUP is the traditional mode of operation in which call setup signalling is done in concert with the ISDN switch. LEASED is a special case of ISDN in which no signalling will be done with the switch and instead the switch is configured with nailed up connections to specific remote ISDN termination points.

wfIsdnBriInterfaceType.name: wfIsdnBriInterfaceType
wfIsdnBriInterfaceType.description: Type of ISDN interface card being used. It can either be 'U' or 'S/T'.

wfIsdnBriNtState.name: wfIsdnBriNtState
wfIsdnBriNtState.description: State of the U interface from the routers point of view. These states correspond to those described in the ANSI T1.601 recommendation and with those described in relation to the IEC-Q.

wfIsdnBriTimerM4Tmo.name: wfIsdnBriTimerM4Tmo
wfIsdnBriTimerM4Tmo.description: Indicates the amount of time in seconds for our M4 timer. The M4 timer is initiated by the host (i.e. the router). The M4 timer is started whenever the host receives a wakeup signal from the U interface. During the duration of the M4 timer, the router in trying to activate the interface will respond with a TN signal followed with SN1 (optional) signal. The router will then receive SL1 from the U interface followed with SL2. Upon reception of SL2 signal, the router will respond with SN2. At this point the timer is stopped if it has not expired yet.

wfIsdnBriTimerM6Tmo.name: wfIsdnBriTimerM6Tmo
wfIsdnBriTimerM6Tmo.description: Indicates the amount of time in milliseconds for our M6 timer. The M6 timer is initiated by the host (i.e. the router). The host has to complete the start-up sequence for the duration of the M6 timer. If it fails to do so, it will enter the receivereset state and remain in that state until it receives a wakeup signal from the U interface.
